# 

# Public API Alpha (v0.2.0)

Common Voice’s Public API allows programmatic access to Common Voice. It allows communities to write custom applications that operate to their specific needs.

# Using the API

## Authentication

In order to access the API you will need a bearer token. You obtain this by making an API call with your API client ID and API client secret. 

### Get API Client ID and Secret

**Important Note**: As of 2025-11-14, this feature has been gated via a feature flag. Normal users will not see this feature, and the method to access will be shared only with Alpha test applications. To be able to see the “API” tab and use it, you need to add `?feature=papi-credentials` to your URL, anywhere on the site, after you log-in. This will create a cookie in your browser, which will be valid for 30 days.

Your API client ID and secret are obtained from the Common Voice website.

1. Head to [https://commonvoice.mozilla.org](https://commonvoice.mozilla.org) and log in and use the feature flag explained above  
2. Click on the dropdown where your username is in the header and select Settings, or go directly to it with the feature flag (required once a month per device/browser):  
   [https://commonvoice.mozilla.org/en/profile/info?feature=papi-credentials](https://commonvoice.mozilla.org/en/profile/info?feature=papi-credentials)   
3. Click API in the left hand menu  
4. Create your new credentials by clicking on the Create API Credentials button  
   1. Enter a name that represents why you created the credentials, such as the project or machine name.  
   2. Agree to the Terms, Privacy Notice and the other conditions for API usage  
   3. Click the Generate Credentials button  
   4. You will be presented with the API Client ID and Secret:![][image1]  
   5. Store your API Client Secret securely as you will never see it again and we cannot recover it for you. Should you lose it, delete the credentials and create a new one

### Get a bearer token

To obtain a bearer token, make an POST request to [`https://api.commonvoice.mozilla.org/auth/token`](https://api.commonvoice.mozilla.org/auth/token) with the following JSON payload:

```json
{
  "clientId": "{Your API Client ID}",
  "clientSecret": "{Your API Client Secret}"
}
```

You also need to set the `Content-Type` header to `application/json`.

In `curl`, it looks like this:

```shell
curl -s https://api.commonvoice.mozilla.org/auth/token \
  -H 'Content-Type: application/json' \
  -d '{"clientId": "{Your API Client ID}", "clientSecret": "{Your API Client Secret}"}'
```

The response is a JSON payload containing a `token` property:

```json
{
  "token": "eyJhbGciOiJSUzI1NiIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCIsImtpZCI6InFLNFhraFNrIn0..eQ6kagHjQ7-6knJadmtGJXStGZEhsINXRiE2dhdGws00NzD9_NXQVGcODlXQ8Dz4nLikgXMZ8ym8CCmWuNprfAMSSEltiM03NGoslmJtKg0cpk3t6Uha9JPT7u81jB1qCWOzlk6-AdMomfBP2ttFRkNs3JPDtzXUSNt8DbFkfi_x2nYIiGha88MzWShHxuGQR9Vb8QGC7Bzgx1hGlTmCGZzyF8y8cxt8NHsxDW-marzlObF0rAX4tXdYFZF7LubI6PxnIAUlPtNqqSva5rqiZl9E56mit-QCfNottFFCesOgJtUSksoQYCAYP-czotgedRc3Z7EHaa62oO7PQNkFJA"
}
```

The token is good for 1 hour and then you will need to get a new one.

### Use the token

In every API call you make, include an `Authorization` header with `Bearer {Your token}`.   
In `curl`, this is done like this: `-H 'Authorization: Bearer {Your token}'`

## The Users API

When submitting data to the public API, a number of endpoints require a user’s User ID. 

To create a user, make a `POST` request to  [`https://api.commonvoice.mozilla.org/auth/users`](https://api.commonvoice.mozilla.org/auth/users) with a JSON body containing `email`  and `username` properties.

In curl, this would be:

```shell
curl -H "Authorization: Bearer {Your token}" \
-H 'Content-Type: application/json' \
"https://api.commonvoice.mozilla.org/auth/users" \
-d '{"email": "janedoe@example.com", "username": "janedoe" }'
```

On success, a response with a `201` status code is returned looking like this:

```json
{
  "data": {
    "userId": "5dbdfbf9-06ee-4445-98b1-93743706502d",
    "username": "janedoe",
    "email": "janedoe@example.com",
    "createdAt": "2024-10-01T12:00:00Z"
  }
}

```

The calling client should store the User ID against the email/username of the user.

The email and username are unique across all users. If the user is already registered, a response with status code `409` is returned looking like this:

```json

{
  "type": "https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTTP/Reference/Status/409",
  "title": "Conflict",
  "status": 409,
  "detail": "A user with this username or email already exists",
  "instance": "/auth/users",
  "message": "User already exists",
  "user": {
    "userId": "5dbdfbf9-06ee-4445-98b1-93743706502d"
  }
}

```

Any other error with the data submitted will return a `400` response of the form:

```json
{
  "type": "https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTTP/Reference/Status/409",
  "title": "Invalid request",
  "status": 400,
  "detail": "The request has incorrect or missing data. Please check your request and try again.",
  "instance": "/auth/users"
}

```

## The Sentences API

The `text/sentences` endpoint provides access to the sentences stored in Common Voice.

Make a `GET` request to [`https://api.commonvoice.mozilla.org/text/sentences`](https://api.commonvoice.mozilla.org/text/sentences). 

The only required query parameter is

* `datasetCode` to select the language (e.g. `cy` for Welsh sentences). The full list is available at `/audio/datasets/codes`

Pagination is controlled via `limit` and `offset` query parameters.

In curl, this would be:

```shell
curl -H "Authorization: Bearer {Your token}" \
"https://api.commonvoice.mozilla.org/text/sentences?datasetCode=cy"
```

The output is a list of sentences in JSON format. For a `limit` of `1`, it looks like this:

```json
{
  "data": [
    {
      "id": "0000cbf805f84c9d7f9eedb4ab60011746a1b5dff1045cde42ab7e9b079661fa",
      "text": "Bellach mae'n cael ei ddeall o ganlyniad i'r model cwarc.",
      "datasetCode": "cy",
      "bucket": "train",
      "version": 10,
      "clipsCount": 0,
      "hasValidClip": false,
      "isValidated": true,
      "source": "covost",
      "domain": "general",
      "variantCode": null,
      "createdAt": "2025-10-30T12:19:13Z",
      "hash": "cba1e09aaffa3257d5540a1286e566bc6995ef1ade25fca1397b72c828058f83"
    }
  ],
  "meta": {
    "offset": 0,
    "limit": 1,
    "returned": 1
  }
}
```

## The Audio Service API endpoints

The audio service has currently the following functionality implemented:

- **Upload**ing an audio with metadata to the processing queue (currently only scripted speech’s sentence readings are supported). The incoming data is recorded into the database, queued and transcoded. The process can be successful or can error out (e.g. bad audio).  
- **Get**ting the status of a single audio using the id, which also returns a URL to the transcoded file, if successful.

### The `/audio` Endpoint

Provides POST access to audio service, for a single audio file with metadata, sent as   
**multipart/form-data**. The API client application should also provide the sentence, its id and hash (exactly the same from the text service), and optional demographic info on the user.

**Required** parameters:

* `file` \- Audio file in supported formats \- supported by ffmpeg/libmp3lame (currently max. 15 seconds for scripted speech, with max. file-size 2,810 kB to also support Wav formats)  
* `resource` \- Currently only `‘scripted’` for scripted-speech (original Common Voice)  
* `datasetCode` \- For single language datasets this will be locale code like `‘en’`, `‘rm-vallader’`, as defined in Pontoon and Common Voice.  
* `textId` \- A hash of the sentence used as id, send back what you get from the text service as it is  
* `text` \- The actual sentence you received from the text service, send back what you get from the text service as it is  
* `hash` \- Hash for authenticity check, send back what you get from the text service as it is  
* `userId` \- Id of the user who did the recording, should be taken from Auth service for each user of the API client application.

**Optional** parameters (demographic info of the user who recorded the sentence aloud):

* `variantCode` \- Variant code of the user, if the language has variants defined  
* `accentCode` \- Predefined-accent code of the user, if the language has predefined-accents  
* `age` \- Age range of the user, as defined in Common Voice, like `‘teens’`, `‘twenties’`, …  
* `gender` \- Gender preference of the user, as defined in Common Voice, like `‘male_masculine’`, `‘female_feminine’`, …

Notes:

* An API client application must send the testId, text, and hash values back to the audio service as they are received from the text service without any changes.  
* All parameters are validated against expected/actual values, and validation error(s) will be returned if a non expected value is posted.  
* All possible values for `age` and `gender` are in the OpenAPI specification and also given below.  
* Possible `datasetCode`, `variantCode`, and `accentCode` values can be reached from the `/audio/datasets/codes` endpoint as summary or detailed, like described below.

Example POST request and response (from Postman) is given below.

#### POST https://api.commonvoice.mozilla.org/audio

![][image2]

Response (202 / accepted status code):

```json
{
    "id": "87b90749-931a-4292-8727-f92108378172",
    "resource": "scripted",
    "datasetCode": "en",
    "accentCode": "england",
    "durationMs": 29832,
    "status": "queued",
    "createdAt": "2025-10-25T15:12:36.861Z",
    "updatedAt": "2025-10-25T15:12:36.861Z",
    "metadata": {
        "age": "sixties",
        "gender": "male_masculine",
        "sentenceId": "000001bd08fb03e61166197ff69755e4c0c064ae71b021355eb3807eae9f363a",
        "sentence": "The album included Who Got Da Props?",
        "upVotes": 0,
        "downVotes": 0
    }
}
```

As can be seen, all data sent to the endpoint gets reported back. In addition, you get back the audio `id`, and several other fields. Status will be initially ‘queued’. The `‘id’` field would be useful if you want to check if the data has been processed correctly or gave errors during transcoding.

Validation error response example (unknown datasetCode and missing required hash):

```json
{
    "type": "https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTTP/Reference/Status/400",
    "status": 400,
    "title": "Validation Failed",
    "detail": "The request contains invalid parameters",
    "instance": "/audio",
    "errors": {
        "datasetCode": "[en-british] is not a valid for dataset or language for [scripted - audio]",
        "hash": "hash should not be empty"
    }
}
```

#### GET https://api.commonvoice.mozilla.org/audio/:id

Queries a single audio record with all its metadata. For example, to get the status of the above POST request:

**GET https://api.commonvoice.mozilla.org/audio/87b90749-931a-4292-8727-f92108378172**

Returns (200 status code):

```json
{
    "id": "87b90749-931a-4292-8727-f92108378172",
    "resource": "scripted",
    "datasetCode": "en",
    "accentCode": "england",
    "durationMs": 29832,
    "url": "http://cv-api-storage:8080/audios/87/87b90749-931a-4292-8727-f92108378172.mp3",
    "status": "pending_validation",
    "createdAt": "2025-10-25T15:12:36.861Z",
    "updatedAt": "2025-10-25T15:12:37.000Z",
    "metadata": {
        "age": "sixties",
        "gender": "male_masculine",
        "sentenceId": "000001bd08fb03e61166197ff69755e4c0c064ae71b021355eb3807eae9f363a",
        "sentence": "The album included Who Got Da Props?",
        "upVotes": 0,
        "downVotes": 0
    }
}
```

As one can see:

* The status has been changed to `‘pending_validation’`, and needs votes. So transcoding has been successful. Otherwise the value would be `‘error’`.  
* A `‘url’` field has been added, which can be used to download the transcoded audio (Note that the URL in the example above is from the local development environment, on production it will be in different format).

We will also be keeping the uploaded original audio during the alpha tests to pinpoint any possible problems.

The voting related endpoint information will be provided when the facilities are fully ready.

## The `/audio/datasets/codes`  API endpoint

This feature is temporarily under the audio service. In the future the functionality will be moved to be part of another new microservice. Therefore, one should define this endpoint as part of the configuration in their clients.  
A `datasetCode` is the language code as defined in Pontoon and Common Voice for single language datasets. We are moving to this concept because of upcoming support for **code-switching** features where a dataset can include multiple languages.

The endpoint supports multiple formats using query parameters:

**GET `https://api.commonvoice.mozilla.org/datasets/`codes\[?service=\<service\>\&resource=\<resource\>\]\[\&detailed\]\[\&datasetCode=\<code\>\]**

* When no query parameter is given it will respond with summary information of all datasets the Common Voice systems support, as an array of JSON objects.  
* The `detailed` flag gives more detailed information with backlinks  
* The `service` and `resource` values complement each other and should be defined as a pair.  
* `service` \- One of `‘text’` or `‘audio’`  
* `resource` \- Currently only `‘scripted’` is supported  
* `datasetCode`\- One of the languages’ code supported by the given `service` and `resource` (which must also be provided). This time it returns a single object, not an array.

- **Valid request patterns (will return json array or single object with 200):**  
  * `GET /datasets/codes` \- *returns all data as summary*  
  * `GET /datasets/codes?detailed` \- *returns all data with more detailed information*  
  * `GET /datasets/codes?service=audio&resource=scripted` \- *returns filtered codes (summary) \- in this example all languages which are eligible to upload scripted audio.*  
  * `GET /datasets/codes?service=text&resource=scripted&detailed` \- *returns filtered codes (detailed) \- in this example all languages which are eligible to upload sentences for scripted speech (not yet supported).*  
  * `GET /datasets/codes?service=audio&resource=scripted&datasetCode=en`  
    *returns only a single record (summary, or detailed if supplied) \- in this example English. This will be useful if your application supports a single language.*

- **Invalid request patterns (will return 400):**  
  * `GET /datasets/codes?service=text` \- *missing resource*  
  * `GET /datasets/codes?resource=scripted` \- *missing service*  
  * `GET /datasets/codes?resource=scripted&datasetCode=en` \- *missing service*

Example validation error response:

```json
{
    "type": "https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTTP/Reference/Status/400",
    "status": 400,
    "title": "Bad Request",
    "detail": "Both service and resource parameters must be provided together, or neither",
    "instance": "/datasets/codes?service=text",
    "message": "Both service and resource parameters must be provided together, or neither",
    "error": "Bad Request"
}
```

So, to get all languages where you can post audio \- as a summary you should use:

**GET `https://api.commonvoice.mozilla.org/datasets/`codes?service=audio\&resource=scripted**

The response is an array of language data or language summary data, in the general format:

```json
[
      {
		...base-language-data
		variants: [...]
		predefined_accents: [...]
      },
...
]
```

The `variants` and `predefined_accents` fields are always present, if there are no values, an empty array `[]` will be presented.

Example summary language object (French)

```json
    {
        "code": "fr",
        "english_name": "French",
        "native_name": "Français",
        "variants": [
            {
                "code": "fr-metro",
                "name": "Français de métropole"
            },
            {
                "code": "fr-europe",
                "name": "Français d'Europe"
            },
            {
                "code": "fr-droum",
                "name": "Français des départements et régions d'outre-mer"
            },
		...
            {
                "code": "fr-asia",
                "name": "Français d'Asie et des îles du Pacifique"
            }
        ],
        "predefined_accents": [
            {
                "code": "fr-metro-south",
                "name": "Français du sud de la France"
            },
		...
            {
                "code": "fr-metro-east",
                "name": "Français de l'est de la France"
            }
        ]
    },




```

Example of detailed language info:

```json
    {
        "id": 104,
        "code": "fr",
        "target_sentence_count": 5000,
        "english_name": "French",
        "native_name": "Français",
        "is_contributable": 0,
        "is_translated": 1,
        "text_direction": "LTR",
        "variants": [
            {
                "id": 2651,
                "code": "fr-metro",
                "name": "Français de métropole",
                "type": null,
                "locale_id": 104
            },
		...
            {
                "id": 2658,
                "code": "fr-asia",
                "name": "Français d'Asie et des îles du Pacifique",
                "type": null,
                "locale_id": 104
            }
        ],
        "predefined_accents": [
            {
                "id": 2478,
                "code": "fr-metro-south",
                "name": "Français du sud de la France",
                "locale_id": 104
            },
		...
            {
                "id": 2481,
                "code": "fr-metro-east",
                "name": "Français de l'est de la France",
                "locale_id": 104
            }
        ]
    },
```

Notes:

* The summary versions (default) will be useful for example to provide language selection. From the provided data, you should filter the ones you support.  
* In the detailed version, all internal data from the Common Voice dataset are also provided. The `text_direction` field can be useful if the application should provide support for both LTR and RTL languages. But applications should reference the objects using the `code` fields, not `id` fields, because these can change depending on the installation \- which will happen when this service goes into a micro-service.  
* We also provide English names of languages as fallback values, in case the native language is not yet provided in Pontoon for that language, which happens when a new language gets created. In these cases, the `native_language` field would contain the language code. The applications can check if `code === native_name`, and if true, can show the English name to the user.  
* This information might get updated with each Common Voice release, which usually happens every week.  
* User provided free-form accents are not supported.

## User Metadata

Common Voice datasets contain metadata that can optionally be associated with users and the clips they record or can be optionally associated with sentences in the text corpus and the corresponding clips of those tagged sentences being read.

### Metadata associated with contributors:

Contributors can optionally include demographic information in their profiles which makes the data they contribute more valuable to dataset users. You may want to configure your application to allow contributors to optionally set age and/or gender markers and associate that metadata with their contributed clips.

Let’s look at what the age metadata table options are and what each corresponds to when associated with a clip.

| Age |  |
| ----- | :---- |
| '' | No age data provided for the user who created this clip |
| twenties | The contributor of this clip has specified that they are aged 20-29. |
| thirties | The contributor of this clip has specified that they are aged 30-39. |
| teens | The contributor of this clip has specified that they are aged 18-19. |
| forties | The contributor of this clip has specified that they are aged 40-49. |
| fifties | The contributor of this clip has specified that they are aged 50-59. |
| sixties | The contributor of this clip has specified that they are aged 60-69. |
| seventies | The contributor of this clip has specified that they are aged 70-79. |
| eighties | The contributor of this clip has specified that they are aged 80-89. |
| nineties | The contributor of this clip has specified that they are aged 90 or above. |

Users can also optionally set their sex or gender identity, let’s look at the table for gender options and what these mean when associated with a clip.

| Gender |  |
| ----- | :---- |
| male\_masculine | The contributor of this clip has specified that they have a male or masculine sex or gender identity. |
| female\_feminine | The contributor of this clip has specified that they have a female or feminine sex or gender identity. |
| 'non-binary' | The contributor of this clip has specified that they have a non-binary sex or gender identity. |
|  | Note: Single quotes must be included in ‘non-binary’ to accommodate the `-` in the field |
| do\_not\_wish\_to\_say | The contributor of this clip has specified that they do not want to share their sex or gender identity. |

### Metadata associated with sentences and clips read from those sentences

Common Voice allows contributors writing or submitting sentences to optionally include a domain to describe what their sentence(s) are about. The metadata of each text sentence is then associated with all clips of this sentence being read.

This metadata may be useful if you want to focus on contributions from a specific sentence domain area in your application. You can find more information about [sentence domains](https://www.mozillafoundation.org/en/blog/domain-datasets-common-voice/) and why they may be useful in this blog post.

| Sentence domains |  |
| ----- | :---- |
| '' | No sentence domain provided for this sentence or clips of it being read. |
| agriculture\_food | This sentence and clips of it being read are about or related to food, agriculture or similar topic areas. |
| automotive\_transport | This sentence and clips of it being read are about or related to modes of transport like cars, planes, trains or about transport or travel more broadly. |
| finance | This sentence and clips of it being read are about or related to money, finance, trade or business. |
| service\_retail | This sentence and clips of it being read are about or related to retail exchanges, purchases or the kinds of language often associated with markets or shops. |
| general | This sentence and clips of it being read do not cover content from any of the other listed sentence domains and have no specialist domain associated with them. |
| healthcare | This sentence and clips of it being read are about or related to health, healthcare, medication or medical services. |
| history\_law\_government | This sentence and clips of it being read are about or related to government, law or history of any current or past location. |
| language\_fundamentals | This sentence and clips of it being read are about or related to the fundamentals of language which may include letters, digits, terms associated with money or other foundational terms used in this language. |
| media\_entertainment | This sentence and clips of it being read are about or related to popular culture, media, entertainment or other recreational topics. |
| nature\_environment | This sentence and clips of it being read are about or related to animals, plants, nature and conservation topics. |
| news\_current\_affairs | This sentence and clips of it being read are about or related to news, current affairs, modern politics and other topics covering things that are happening in the world today. |
| technology\_robotics | This sentence and clips of it being read are about or related to technology, computers, programming, AI or robotics more broadly. |

### 

### User Variants and Accents

These are both associated to the selected dataset and to the user data. For a single language dataset, as specified above under `/audio/datasets/codes`, there are predefined variants and accents, which are defined in the returned code under `variants[]` and `predefined_accents[]` arrays.

Variants can be assigned to:  
\- Sentences (e.g. sentences in different scripts, retrieval of them are not yet supported)  
\- Audio postings (user’s variant and accent)

The API client applications’ users should be able to post this information while contributing to a specific single-language dataset, but the codes MUST match the ones in that language. These codes will be validated and only allowed data will be accepted, else a validation error will be returned.
